gral part of working safely at GE. The prevention program ensures that proper safety information is in place; operating procedures are followed; chemical hazards are identified; employees and contractors are trained; and critical equipment is properly inspected and maintained. Our prevention program meets all aspects of the accidental release prevention program requirements of the EPA's Risk Management Program.

There are many specific safety features in place at the facility. Some of the features in place at GE Kentucky Glass facility to prevent a chemical accident include:

* Safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error which could lead to a storage tank overfill;

* Secondary containment dike at the tank truck off-loading area to contain the full contents of the tank truck;

* Secondary containment dikes around the chemical storage tanks to contain a spill;

* Full enclosure of the storage tanks in a separate on-site building;

* Operation of a fume scrubber which removes chemicals from the air exhausted from within the chemical storage and working areas;

* Extensive safety information about the processes available to employees;

* Written operating procedures that identify plant policies on emergency response actions;

* Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work-practices;

* Scheduled maintenance programs to ensure equipment reliability - includes equipment testing and inspections;

* Compliance auditing to ensure standards are being followed;

* A safety procedure to review proposed plant modifications before they are implemented for possible hazards; 

* Annual HF training for Frost personnel plant employees, management and environmental, health and safety personnel.

* Safety reviews prior to startup of our processes; and

* Annual exercises with local Fire Dept, Hazmat Team, police, hospital ER and internal personnel.

